Improved performance under JDK 8.

A new configuration option `defaultSqlProviderType` is added. The specified class will be used as the SQL provider when the `value` or `type` is not specified in `@SelectProvider`, `@UpdateProvider`, `@InsertProvider` and `@DeleteProvider`.
A new transaction isolation level `SQL_SERVER_SNAPSHOT` is added to `TransactionIsolationLevel` enum to support the MS SQL Server specific isolation level `SNAPSHOT`.
When there is no [JEP-290 serialization filter] defined, a WARN level message is logged on deserializing object streams.
Possible `NoSuchPropertyException` under heavy load.
Possible `InvalidPathException` when registering type aliases by specifying package name.
Possible `OutOfMemoryError` when using `BlockingCache`.
You can reference single `List` or `Collection` type parameter using its actual parameter name when `useActualParamName` is enabled.
You can specify `resultMap` in `@One` and `@Many`.
You can specify `columnPrefix` in `@One` and `@Many`.
A new option `shrinkWhitespacesInSql` to remove extra whitespaces in SQL.
Possible IllegalArgumentException when using `@CacheNamespaceRef` .
Mapper method invocation should be non-blocking work around JDK-8161372.
You can now omit unnecessary `@Results` and `@ConstructorArgs` annotation.
Avoid invoking hashCode method when setting auto-generated keys.
Possible ResultMapException when using nested select.
Possible incorrect TypeVariable resolution in TypeParameterResolver.
Race condition in TypeHandlerRegistry.
Support variable substitution in CDATA of included `<sql />`.
Support default method invocation on JDK 14+8 or later.
Avoid illegal reflective access warning when invoking default mapper method.
Ambiguous getter/setter now throws ReflectionException only when it is actually accessed.
Possible infinite loop when a SQL provider throws an exception.
Unable to iterate Cursor if the next element is null.
queryCursor fails in streaming mode of MySQL Connector/J.
SQL builder now supports LIMIT, OFFSET  and FETCH FIRST
SQL builder now supports multi-row insert syntax
A new property `defaultNetworkTimeout` has been added to the built-in data sources i.e. `PooledDataSource` and `UnpooledDataSource`
SQL provider annotations now takes `value` attribute which is an alias for `type`
You can now pass Java array to `ArrayTypeHandler#setNonNullParameter`
You can reference single simple type unnamed parameter with any name in OGNL expressions
A new configuration option `defaultResultSetType` is added
SQL provider method with a primitive parameter causes BuilderException
Fixes a possible `NullPointerException`
`keyProperty` specified with parameter name could cause ExecutorException.
False positive error 'Ambiguous collection type ...' .
`EnumTypeHandler` is not used when the enum has methods.
Auto-mapping fails in a result map referenced from a constructor arg with `columnPrefix`.
Constructor auto-mapping could fail when `columnPrefix` is specified in the parent result map.
`LocalTimeTypeHandler` loses fractional seconds part.
`LocalDateTypeHandler` and `LocalDateTimeTypeHandler` could return unexpected value.
You can now return 'script' from a SQL provider. The returned script is parsed using the language driver specified by `@Lang`.
You can now omit `method` attribute from SQL provider annotations when the provider method has the same name as the mapper method or its name is `provideSql`.
You can now get `databaseId` in SQL providers.
The default type handler for `LONGVARCHAR` is changed from `ClobTypeHandler` to `StringTypeHandler`. This improves compatibility with SAP ASE.
Avoid 'Illegal reflective access' warning on JDK 9+.
Added Automatic-Module-Name : org.mybatis
Support java.util.Optional as return type of mapper method.
Avoid unnecessary `wasNull` calls from the built-in type handlers.
It is now possible to specify `columnPrefix` in constructor arguments.
Improved reliability when searching constructor for auto-mapping.
It is now possible to access private, package private and protected members in OGNL expressions.
Throw exception if the specified keyProperty is not found when assigning generated keys.
Added a type handler for SQLXML data type.
Allow accessing private, package private and protected members in OGNL expression.
`<set />` tag now trims the leading comma.
Infer `<case />` tag's `resultType` from the enclosing `resultMap`.
Allow specifying `columnPrefix` in constructor mapping.
Combination of `@CacheNamespace` and `<cache-ref />` does not throw exception anymore.
Support Log4J 2.6+.
Slightly improved compatibility with drivers that only support JDBC 3 API.
Upgraded testing framework to JUnit 5.
OffsetDateTimeTypeHandler, OffsetTimeTypeHandler and ZonedDateTimeTypeHandler loses time zone information.
Avoid SQLException when using `Cursor` with Db2.
Avoid exception when using `Cursor` with ReuseExecutor.
RowBounds with out-of-range offset causes SQLException on DB2.
Specified logging implementation is not used in some classes.
Unable to resolve `javaType` for `<association />`.
Deeply nested 3+ levels result map could cause IllegalArgumentException.
Generic type parameter is not correctly resolved when the class hierarchy is deeper than 3 levels.
Apply custom ResultHandler to CURSOR type OUT parameter.
Substitute variables in attribute values of included SQL fragments.
BatchExecutor now closes each statement immediately after execution.
It is now possible to use a static method as SQL provider.
SQL provider method can now return CharSequence instead of String.
Add resource path to the exception message when parsing XML mapper failed.
Registering type handler against HashMap causes ClassCastException.
Unable to register TypeHandler once TypeHandlerRegistry.hasTypeHandler is called.
Serializing and deserializing cached objects causes NullPointerException.
Invalid error message 'Two methods with same method signature but not providing classes assignable?' in System.err.
Make default enum type handler customizable.
Make mapper method and its interface type accessible to SqlProvider.
Allow using configuration properties in SqlProvider.
Merge type handlers for JSR-310 Java Date and Time API into the core.
The type handler registered for a common interface of enums was not applied correctly.
Lazy loading should not overwrite a property value set by user.
Prevent foreach xml tag from polluting the global context.
Some parameter names e.g. 'size' can cause ClassCastException.
Not all result sets are processed when UPDATE or INSERT is performed in between.
With PostgreSQL, ExecutorException is thrown if `useGeneratedKeys` is enabled globally.
Allow registering a type handler for a common interface of enums.
Share Jdbc3KeyGenerator and NoKeyGenerator instances
Building UPDATE JOIN statement by SQL Builder
Failed to find a statement mapped to a super interface
Default methods support on mappers, does not work for non-public mappers.
foreignColumns with multiple columns validation error
Fix wrong registration logic for LanguageDriver
A boolean property should be able to have two getters: isX and getX
Possible unexpected auto-mapping
Excessive memory allocation for primitive arrays in nested resultmaps
New option 'returnInstanceForEmptyRow' to control the behavior when a query returns a row with all columuns being `null`.
Support 'default methods' on mapper interfaces.
When no type handler is registered to a class, a type handler registered to its superclass can be used.
New attributes `properties` is added to `@CacheNamespace`.
New attributes `name` is added to `@CacheNamespaceRef`.
Support the mechanism for initializing a cache after set all properties.
Allow users to set default value in placeholders.
Auto-detecting type handlers newly added in version 1.0.2 of TypeHandlers-JSR310.
Allow referencing parameters by their declared names when compiled with Java 8 `-parameters` option.
Added auto-detection of Year/MonthTypeHandler added in mybatis-typehandlers-jsr310 1.0.1.
`@Select` can now return an array of objects.
Allow specifying custom `reflectorFactory` in XML config.
Circularly referenced resultMap was filled with ancestor object even when columnPrefix was specified.
Select statement with `@Param` couldn't be used as a nested select statement of association.

If autoscaling is enabled for machine learning, the administrator of the cluster should increase the cluster setting `xpack.ml.max_open_jobs` to the maximum value of `512`. This allows autoscaling to run reliably as it relies on assigning jobs only via memory. Having `xpack.ml.max_open_jobs` as a small number may cause autoscaling to behave unexpectedly.

Snapshot and restore: If an index is deleted while the cluster is concurrently taking more than one snapshot then there is a risk that one of the snapshots may never complete and also that some shard data may be lost from the repository, causing future restore operations to fail. To mitigate this problem, prevent concurrent snapshot operations by setting `snapshot.max_concurrent_operations: 1`.

A document disclosure flaw was found in the Elasticsearch suggester and profile API when Document and Field Level Security are enabled. The suggester and profile API are normally disabled for an index when document level security is enabled on the index. Certain queries are able to enable the profiler and suggester which could lead to disclosing the existence of documents and fields the attacker should not be able to view. All versions of Elasticsearch before 6.8.15 and 7.11.2 are affected by this flaw. You must upgrade to 6.8.15 or 7.11.2 to obtain the fix. [CVE-2021-22137]

Integration with [Active Directory realms]active-directory-realm.html "Active Directory user authentication" and [LDAP realms]ldap-realm.html "LDAP user authentication" is impacted by an issue that prevents Elasticsearch from starting. If you have configured an Active Directory or LDAP realm, then Elasticseach will fail to start with an error message indicating that `Could not initialize class com.unboundid.util.Debug`. This exception is fatal. If you encounter this during an upgrade, because Elasticsearch failed during node construction, you can safely downgrade to your previous version of Elasticsearch. Note: these downgrade instructions only apply if you encounter this specific error message; in general, downgrades are not safe. Elasticsearch 7.11.1 will contain a fix for this issue. For more details, see

If autoscaling is enabled for machine learning, the administrator of the cluster should increase the cluster setting `xpack.ml.max_open_jobs` to the maximum value of `512`. This allows autoscaling to run reliably as it relies on assigning jobs only via memory. Having `xpack.ml.max_open_jobs` as a small number may cause autoscaling to behave unexpectedly.

If autoscaling is enabled and job assignment takes an inordinate amount of time, scaling sizes may increase much higher than required. Elasticsearch 7.13.0 contains a fix for this. For more details, see

Snapshot and restore: If an index is deleted while the cluster is concurrently taking more than one snapshot then there is a risk that one of the snapshots may never complete and also that some shard data may be lost from the repository, causing future restore operations to fail. To mitigate this problem, prevent concurrent snapshot operations by setting `snapshot.max_concurrent_operations: 1`.

An information disclosure flaw was found in the Elasticsearch async search API. Users who execute an async search will store the HTTP headers. A user with the ability to read the `.tasks` index could obtain sensitive request headers of other users in the cluster. All versions of Elasticsearch between 7.7.0 and 7.10.1 are affected by this flaw. You must upgrade to Elasticsearch version 7.10.2 to obtain the fix. [CVE-2021-22132]

Elasticsearch versions before 7.10.0 and 6.8.14 have an information disclosure issue when audit logging and the `emit_request_body` option are enabled. The Elasticsearch audit log could contain sensitive information, such as password hashes or authentication tokens. This could allow an Elasticsearch administrator to view these details. You must upgrade to Elasticsearch version 7.10.0 to obtain the fix. [CVE-2020-7021]

SQL: If a `WHERE` clause contains at least two relational operators joined by `AND`, of which one is a comparison `<=`, `<`, `>=`, `>` and another one is an inequality `!=`, `<>`, both against literals or foldable expressions, the inequality will be ignored. The workaround is to substitute the inequality with a `NOT IN` operator.

With multiple layers of nested `inner_hits`, we can fail to load the _source.
With nested `inner_hits`, the fast vector highlighter may load snippets from the wrong document.
When _source is disabled, we can fail load nested `inner_hits` and `top_hits`.

New instance properties: `$attrs` & `$listeners`. `$attrs` contains the parent-scope attribute bindings that were not recognized as props, and `$listeners` contains the `v-on` listeners registered in the parent scope without the `.native` modifier. These are essentially aliases of `$vnode.data.attrs` and `$vnode.data.on`, but are reactive.

When using `v-for` with a component, a `key` is now required. You will likely see a bunch of "soft warnings" when you upgrade, but this does not affect the current behavior of your app.

The template parser will now raise errors for tags that are missing matching closing tags. Although a tag without matching closing tag is vaild in HTML5, it is most of the time an unintentional mistake, and can lead to subtle bugs. This check does not work for in-DOM templates because the HTML string is already normalized by the browser before being passed to Vue's parser.

Props and computed properties are now defined on a component's prototype instead of as self properties on each instance. This avoids many calls to `Object.defineProperty` and improves component initialization performance. This will only affect you if you rely on `hasOwnProperty` checks on props and computed properties, which should be extremely rare, but we are documenting it here to be explicit about the change. relevant commits: [`406352b`] [`e870e6c`]

If you previously relied on `try...catch` for handling possible errors in component lifecycle hooks, the errors will no longer be thrown directly. However, you can use the global `Vue.config.errorHandler` to intercept and handle those errors.

Many exposed methods and properties on `Vue.util` have been removed. If you previously relied on them, you should migrate off of them since this object is intended for internal use only - it is not and has never been considered part of the public API and may change without notice in the future.

The default export used by Webpack 2 will now point to an ES module build `dist/vue.runtime.esm.js`. This means without any alias configuration, `require'vue'` in webpack 2 will give you an object `{ __esModule: true, default: Vue }` instead. You should only use `import Vue from 'vue'` with webpack 2.

`v-leave-active`: applied across the entire transition duration.

Functional components:
A functional component has no instance and is simply a function that receives props and children vnodes via arguments, and also return vnodes.
Unlike stateful components, functional components are not restricted by the "single root node" rule and can return an Array of multiple vnodes.
A functional component's render function receives the following arguments:
`createElement`: the parent component's `$createElement` method.
`props`: an object containing props
`children`: children inside the component's tag as vnodes

Transition definitions can now specify the type of CSS effect it should wait for, either `transition` or `animation`. This is only necessary in situations where you explicitly want Vue's transition system to only care about one type while being able to use the other type. For example, you may want Vue's transition to be based on a CSS animation, but the element also has CSS transition effects on hover.

Transition definitions can now specify the `enterClass` and `leaveClass` for CSS-based transitions. This will override the conventional class names. Useful when you want to combine Vue's transition system with an existing CSS animation library, e.g. [Animate.css]
